<hr />

<ul>
  <li><strong>Focus on the 20% of actions needed to accomplish 80% of what matters.</strong></li>
</ul>

<p>A windmill might look like it‚Äôs spinning so fast, but still it doesn‚Äôt go anywhere. Focus on expanding your strengths.  Don‚Äôt confuse action with motion‚Ä®.  Instead of running around in circles, take clear action steps towards your purpose. Feeling like you are always doing so much and keeping yourself busy is a waste of energy.</p>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li><strong>One Task</strong> Cut down on multitasking.</li>
</ul>

<p>Make it stupidly small. You predict failure when you don‚Äôt understand what you need to do. Never, ever, ever have an ominous task on your list. Even ‚Äúdo my taxes‚Äù is too vague. How do you do that? Where do you get started? More importantly: what is the smallest step you can do today and make any progress towards that goal? Break down a big idea into small bits. Collect ‚Äústupidly small‚Äù tasks you can knock out with minimal anguish. We‚Äôre looking to build a good predictive model where you succeed at doing things, no matter how small.</p>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li><strong>Do deep work early morning.</strong> Leave distractions for commute time or for after you‚Äôve done your most important task of day.</li>
</ul>

<blockquote>
  <p>Deep Work: ‚ÄúProfessional activity performed in a state of distraction-free concentration that push your cognitive capabilities to their limit. These efforts create new value, improve your skill, and are hard to replicate.‚Äù</p>
</blockquote>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li><strong>Give yourself 1/3 of the time to finish most tasks</strong>  Always demand a deadline. A deadline weeds out the extraneous and the ordinary. It prevents you from trying to make it perfect, so you have to make it different. Different is better. You might guess that researching a topic for a 1500 word essay takes around 3 hours. This strategy proposes that you give yourself 1.5 hours instead. Finish your work by 5:30 P.M ‚Äì Fixed-schedule productivity ‚Äì Do what is necessary and interesting.</li>
</ul>

<p>Don‚Äôt go out too hard. Novice runners often mistake running for sprinting. They go out for a ‚Äúrun‚Äù, sprint for a mile until they‚Äôre out of breath and then vow to never repeat the experience. Sprinting is hard! Don‚Äôt start with that. Maximize enjoyment. Run at the easiest pace you can manage. Find a scenic place. Enjoy the fresh air, if you can find it. Your goal is to make memories that are pleasant. Similarly, you‚Äôre working through a project, try to start off my making it as fun as possible. One way to do this is to split a problem into small, bite-sized components, since it‚Äôs satisfying to mark something as done. Or reward yourself by working on a novel part of the problem first.</p>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li><strong>Keep making it until it doesn‚Äôt feel like you‚Äôre faking it, because you actually aren‚Äôt becaue there ain‚Äôt no such thing as perfect and there‚Äôs always room for improvement.</strong></li>
</ul>

<p>You only learn from deliberative practice.</p>

<p>A mistake is an evaluation of an action. An action is in your control. The evaluation should be left to others. <sup id="fnref:interview"><a href="#fn:interview" class="footnote">1</a></sup></p>

<p>‚ÄúFake it until you make it‚Äù gets it wrong. It makes you feel like an impostor. If you‚Äôre mindful of faking it, you‚Äôre not practicing the thing, but practicing faking it. If you learn to act like someone who is a good storyteller, you won‚Äôt be a good storyteller, but you‚Äôd be a good actor.</p>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li><strong>Excellence is mundane</strong>.  Excellence is accomplished through the doing of actions, ordinary in themselves, performed consistently and carefully, habitualized, compounded together, added up over time. The action in itself is nothing special, the care and consistency with which it is made is special.
    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://fermatslibrary.com/s/the-mundanity-of-excellence-an-ethnographic-report-on-stratification-and-olympic-swimmers">Mundanity of Excellence</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://firstround.com/review/the-founders-guide-to-discipline-lessons-from-fronts-mathilde-collin/">Discipline</a></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<blockquote>
  <p>‚ÄúFrom the very first session, I could sense something different,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know, something. Not just him, all of his staff. The way we trained, the way they saw football, the way they worked, prepared games. A relentless, even intimidating, work ethic. It really struck me. And I said to myself: ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt waste a year of my career not working with this coach.‚Äô‚Äù</p>
</blockquote>

<hr />

<ul>
  <li><strong><a href="/winning">Identify as a winner</a></strong>.</li>
</ul>

<p>If you identify as an athlete, and you talk to yourself and others with that expectation, then that is much more effective than ‚ÄúI need to get in better shape‚Äù. When you identify with something it compels your actions, almost by default, much more than willpower alone. Trust yourself and then performing to the full potential in full presence with full application of the mind <a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=18938860">Link</a></p>

<p>It matters that you <strong>believe in yourself</strong> and trust yourself rather than being pessimistic, understating your abilities, or thinking the task before you too hard.</p>
<blockquote>
  <p>Whether you believe you can or can‚Äôt, it‚Äôs true.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Visualization. Just fantasize. What will you do when you pay your taxes? Direct a movie in your mind. Some parts of it will provoke a neutral reaction. Some will be negative (‚Äúugh, gotta assemble lots of documents‚Ä¶ BORING!‚Äù). You‚Äôre feeding your brain positive training data to make the act of doing the task less daunting. You‚Äôre demystifying it. Athletes who visualize their sport find improved performance. Become an Olympian in productivity.</p>

<p>Celebrate success. Once you achieve something challenging, your goal is to remember it as much as possible. You want your mind to store the positive moment as motivation fuel for next time. With running, some of this comes for free (the biochemical effects of a ‚Äúrunner‚Äôs high‚Äù), but you can get it for other tasks as well: tell your friends what you did! If you made it through a book, discuss it with others. If you finished some part of a side-project, show it off! It‚Äôs fun to get feedback from other people, especially if you respect them.</p>

