<ul>
  <li><strong>Act now</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>The essence of improving is action.</li>
      <li>Act in order to discover what comes next.</li>
      <li>You don‚Äôt need to feel like doing something to do it.</li>
      <li>Schedule a difficult task and stick to your timetable.</li>
      <li>Invite a buddy to join you in doing what you need to do.</li>
      <li>Do the hard things first.</li>
      <li>To find a new perspective, try doing something a different way.</li>
      <li>Sometimes <em>not doing</em> is what is needed.</li>
      <li>If you can‚Äôt get out of it, <em>get into it</em>.</li>
      <li>Don‚Äôt believe in getting into the zone.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<blockquote>
  <p>The ego is the enemy of the imagination. Anything that you think about writing when you‚Äôre not writing, is a product of the ego and is absolutely wrong. One hundred percent, all the time, wrong. And if take a step back and think how much time you spend trying to purify yourself in order to get ready to write, that‚Äôs like 95% of the time. And the reason for that is the ego has a stake in perpetuating the behavior that you‚Äôve already engaged in. We do not think our way to right action; we act our way to right thinking.
So what I do is I start writing. If I think about my writing before I start to write, what I‚Äôm really doing is justifying not writing, because ‚Ä¶ I‚Äôm not writing. ‚Ä¶ I‚Äôm going to find a way to keep not writing. So what I say is I don‚Äôt have the idea yet; it‚Äôs not fully realized yet‚Ä¶ Not only that: I don‚Äôt have pencils; my pencils are not sharpened; I don‚Äôt have the right notebook. ‚Ä¶ Whoa! Eleven-forty five already. Time for lunch.
‚Ä¶ When you think about exercising, what you invariably say to yourself is, ‚ÄúYou know, I‚Äôm too fat. What‚Äôs the point? I‚Äôm too old; I‚Äôm too fat; I‚Äôm too old; I‚Äôm too slow; I‚Äôm too this; I‚Äôm too that‚Ä¶‚Äù And all you‚Äôre doing is justifying the fact that you‚Äôre not exercising.
People went to ‚Äúget in the zone,‚Äù because they hope to write something inspired or perfect or smart immediately. I don‚Äôt know any professional writers who expect that.
Instead, we just start writing and let whatever garbage we spew out land on the page or screen. Then make a second draft. Then a third, and so on, each time, pruning away a bit more of the garbage, keeping the few gems that somehow found their way into the garbage can, and shaping some of the semi-garbage into something useful. - 
‚ÄúGetting into the zone‚Äù is not writing. When I want to write, I write. When I don‚Äôt want to write, I write. Because that‚Äôs what writers do. TV writer David Milch, creator of ‚ÄúDeadwood.‚Äù</p>
</blockquote>

